sql:
SELECT DISTINCT student_id
FROM results
WHERE passing_status = 'Pass';

SELECT student_id
FROM scores
WHERE average_score > (SELECT AVG(average_score) FROM scores);

external_knowledge:
- 'Rise of stars' is a metaphor for students performing well; 
- 'Final exam' corresponds to the 'Final Paper' assessment; 
- 'Shine with a grade of at least B' refers to grades 'B', 'A', 'A-', 'B+', and 'A+';
- Courses are represented by `course_id`.

sql:
SELECT students.gender, scores.average_score
FROM students 
INNER JOIN scores ON students.student_id = scores.student_id;

external_knowledge:
- "sea of data" refers to the database;
- "mathematical and reading achievements" corresponds to math_score and reading_score;
- "the course they sail in" represents the course identifier (course_id);
- "waves they have navigated" is a metaphor for attendance status (Present, Absent, Late);
- "performance beacon" symbolizes the performance range name (Good, Excellent);
- "charted waters of the performance chart" signifies the average score lying between the lower_bound and upper_bound of the performance ranges.

sql:
SELECT range_name
FROM performance_ranges
WHERE lower_bound >= 80 AND upper_bound <= 90;

external_knowledge:
- Doing well implies an average score greater than 80;
- Frequently present means having an attendance rate of at least 75%;
- Performance range names like "Good" or "Excellent" indicate how well a student is performing based on their average scores.
